ass=title> Absolution....</span><hr size=1> The chill seeped further in to her as she moved deeper along the frozen path. All around her there was nothing but ice and snow. Her only companion on this trip was her spirit wolf, again he turned to look at her as if to ask her why. Sighing she knew that she could not get away with out answering him. For some reason he had away of getting any thing out of her that she did not want to speak about, and with only a simple look too. He gave a soft woof and she looked at him again before groaning, knowing full well that he would not give up. Years of being together had made it easy for him to learn her ways and how to deal with her. No matter how much it irritated her that he could, she always felt better after talking to the one being who totally understood her. <br>
<br>
&quot; You know why, but I will tell you again, only the ice and snow of home can ease this pain.&quot; <br>
<br>
If a wolf could be said to give a doubting look he was giving her one at that point. Conveying his thoughts to her as he always had and questioning her decision yet again. It was all she could do not to turn and look at him with her hands on her hips.  She should have known that he would be this troublesome about this, he had grown to like the guild hall way to much, that and the warm weather. She gave him a disgusted look before speaking again to him. <br>
<br>
&quot; I need this wolf, it is the only way that I can get though this and remain myself. And yes they are my family too but this I know they can not help with. At least not at this point, maybe once I have completed the first three waves of the cleansing ceremony I will be able to return to the guild hall. Until them give over and let it rest will you?&quot;<br>
<br>
Silence came after that and she was thankful for it, the grief and turmoil that she had helped her friend with settled heavily on her shoulders. Since she had come in to her natural ability as a shaman, she had helped those who needed it. Some times it was only using a healing spell, other times it was it was more of a spiritual heal that took a lot out of her. This time the pull had been so strong that it overrode every thing else. The moment she had seen him, she had known that if she helped him it might destroy her. Looking up she saw the cabin against the snow and smiled, for the first time in weeks. Sanctuary, it beckoned to her, almost as if calling to her on a spiritual level. Here she would be able to work thought the grief she had taken in to herself to ease him of the pain that bound him. It had not been easy to walk that road with him, to see and feel every thing over and over till she could take it away.  Only her training made it so that she could keep herself separate, but that did not stop her from feeling it. <br>
<br>
It had taken her some time to get him to open up to her,  and to trust her enough that he did not give her that indifferent look all the time. Once the connection was made she had little trouble leaching out the pain and distrust that  was wrapped around his heart. At first she ahd simply asked for his help on a few quests that she had been given. She gained his trust and listened to him when he had finally managed to talk about his past. Working with him day after day allowed a friendship to form, one that meant more to her than most. She could not help that she had fallen a little in love with him. His caring nature and the sense of humor that very few actually got to see had warmed her, after she had chipped the ice form where it had no place being. <br>
<br>
She had thought that after every thing, he might have felt the same for her but she would never know now. They had been getting ready to start another quest when there had been some kind of mist that formed in front fo them. A woman walked out of it and it only took one look at his face for her to see that this was the one person she could never compete with.  How could a barbarian compare to the grave and beauty of the elves, as she thought that it was confirmed when he stood up. She saw him start to walk towards the stranger, standing herself she took one look at him and then cast the spell that would send her home. She had not even waited to see if he would look back at her, instead she had been greeted by a blast of cold and her wolf companion as she entered Everfrost.<br>
<br>
That was how she had come to be standing in front of her old cabin, and the one place she knew that she would be at peace. Walking in to the cabin she could tell that it needed some work to make it suitable for her to stay in. Stretching she got right to work and had it ready in less time that she thought she would, the roof was in good condition and once she had a fire going it was warmed up the cabin quickly. She cleaned up all the snow that had managed to come in though the rear door. Once she had everything cleaned she unpacked all the supplies that she had brought with her. Turning she headed in to one of the other two rooms, making sure that the bedroom was fit for sleeping in and that her ritual room was intact. She looked around and could almost feel peace seeping in to her just from being in her ritual room. Every thing was where she had left it and knowing that made it so that she could relax at least a little bit. <br>
<br>
She knew that she had some time before she needed to start the first ritual, walking back out to the main room she quickly fixed some food and watched the fire while she ate. When the appointed hour came she rose from the chair she was in and moved in to her ritual room. Lighting several candles, she asked her wolf to guard her while she slipped in to the first level of meditation. Softly the words of power came from her mouth, weaving her deeper in to the center of her spirit. She knew that there was a price for absolution, but she knew her Gods would not take her life for easing the pain. The meditation took on a trance like quality as she offered herself up to the Tribunal for judgment, her body relaxing as her spirit was transported to a different plane. <br>
<br>
~~ She stood before then and waited for the first to speak, the voice was quiet and sounded more in her head than as if actually spoken. Again she was before them but this time she was here for absolution and to have the peace that she needed from the pain. They knew why she was there and waited several moments before asking her if she was sure it was what she wanted. Having gone though it before she knew some of what would be taken for her but since it had become partly personal, it would hurt a lot more. Standing tall she looked at each of them before nodding her head and speaking again. <br>
<br>
&quot; I wish absolution, and seek it here, I know the price and am willing to pay.&quot;<br>
<br>
Every thing around her went black and she closed her eyes, feeling some thing slip in to her mind and sifting though all of her memories of the pain and her helping him. Her soul screamed over and over as she was made to relive everything again, seeing him so quiet and looking alone. The pull of needing to help him in what ever way that she could, then helping him to open up once again and trust. Tears burned her soul as they washed away the pain of reliving his past hurt, and then it started on her own pain. There was a wrenching in her heart as she watched their last parting before she had come home to EverFrost. Again she saw him looking at his lost love and knew that there was nothing more that she could do but wish him happy. Never could she mention the emotions that were hidden deep inside her, to do so would only cause more pain for all of them. After some time she felt the cooling feel of justice, as it washed though her and eased the pain. Forming a layer of ice around her to protect her until she was ready to help the next one that needed her. <br>
<br>
&quot; Thank you.&quot; <br>
<br>
It was simply said but she knew that they were aware of how much this meant to her, now she could return and start again. Light flooded the area where she was kneeling and when she opened her eyes again she was back in her body. Little did she know that it had taken three days for them to give her the what she had been seeking, or that over time if she did not learn to care again the ice would stay there permanently. ~~<br>
<br>
Stretching cramped muscles she turned her head and looked at her wolf, wondering how long she had been in her trance. From the look of things she would have guessed three days at the least. It took a lot of effort to actually stand and she walked in to the main room of her cabin, starting a fire before cooking some thing for her to eat. She wanted to give it a little more time before she had to face the world and every thing that was in it, along with the people that she would have to see at some point. Once her food was ready she went back to sit in front of the fire and her companion came to sit beside her, offering what comfort he could. He told her with out words that it was the morning of the fourth day and that all three waves of the ritual were completed. It surprised her that the Tribunal had done all three steps at the same time, but it was their will to do it as they saw fit. She had a vague sense that he had some thing else to tell her but was unsure if she would want to know it at that point, sighting she looked at him. <br>
<br>
&quot; What it is friend?&quot;<br>
<br>
In their way of communicating he told her of the visitor that had come to see her, only to leave again before she had come out of her healing trance. Kallren frowned and wondered who it could have been that had been there, she knew deep down that it would not have been the one she healed. There would never be a place for her with him again, sadness throbbed though her and the ice hardened, soothing the ache and lessening the pain again. Absently she wondered if she would ever be able to think about him with out needing the soothing cold that followed the absolution. Shaking her head she let it go and looked again at her wolf. <br>
<br>
&quot; Well maybe at some point we will meet who it was again and see if they need my help. Right now I just want to relax for a day or two before we head back to the land of the elves.&quot;<br>
<br>
Silence followed that statement and she was content for the moment just to watch the fire burn and relax as much as she could. There were so many thing that she thought about but soon it was all forgotten as the fire consumed the wood. Tomorrow would be another day and she knew that there was more to this life than what she had already experienced. <br>
