t from the land of trees and elves.  Someone was missing.  The man spoke of how a couple had gone out.  One was still unaccounted for but for some reason noone knew where she was but was fairly sure she was alive.  Going on he spoke of how she had disappeared and where she had stood the grass was left frozen and coverd with ice and snow.  Klinget had seen similar happenings many times before in many different ways.  Small areas left burnt, sometimes covered in sand, but to have done this he knew it had to have been a magical gate opened to a harsh and frozen land.  From the description he received he thought he might know who this person was, and if it was he might know where they were going.  This place was far from any outpost, or anything for that fact but ice and snow.  He wondered if jumping from that fair climate to one so cold if the person had been prepared even.  This is what he now set out to find.  This would lead him far off his direct route and called for many more supplies, especially if he needed to help this person. <br>
<br>
      The direction he chose would not be the safest but much quicker.  He did not worry though, the only things he knew that would threaten him would be a few small bands of goblins, and they posed no threat as long as their numbers were small.  Other times though it would be much more dangerous because the tribes of goblins were known to get quiet large but they were warring among themselves and remained small with no treaty.  He set camp when he had to making traps with what he could.  Most the traps were more alarms then mortal.  He slept with his weapons drawn at night in case of any intruders with mal intent.  For several nights he done so with no incidence but knew that he had been noticed and it would only be a matter of time if he did not leave their territory soon.  <br>
<br>
  He had set up camp early and hastily with a storm on the horizon.  Not taking the usual care in his traps he had focused more upon his shelter, he would need it to survive the night.  He fell asleep to the howls of the blizzard that came.<br>
<br>
  And that night they came.  He laid on his side weapon drawn and his back to a rock he used as part of his shelter.  He awoke to the sound of a bloodied gurgle and grasped his sword.  He thought to himself how foolish he was to think nothing would come out in this storm.  His eyes quickly adjusted to the odd darkness that was cast by the blizzard and made out what seemed to be two set of small legs shuffling toward him.  He grit his teeth as they came closer biding his time till they were in reach of his blades.  He could hear more though, but how many could there be he wondered.  He could now make out they were goblins.  As the two came upon him they stopped and one bent down.  As the one did this Klinget quickly drew his dagger and sank it in the creatures gut while jumping to his feet and quickly spinning around landing his sword blade in the side of the puny goblin and cleaving him in half.  This action set the camp alive with shrieks and howls.  He knew there was no use in running and it would be certain death to leave his supplies behind anyhow.  So he grit his teeth and drew his second blade and with a howl that echoed through the winds charged out of his lean to. Charging out he was surrounded by the creatures many carrying torches and many wielding crude weapons.  The goblins cowardly by nature were startled and some ran off but most turned upon him. Keeping their distance from him the first to attack came from behind leaping on his back off the rock he used for cover.  The goblin stabbed at his side and would have been mortal if the crude weapon did not break upon his armor. Quickly slinging the thing from his back and stabbing it as it landed the rest charged him.  Slashing them as they charged they still managed to get close enough to grab him which he would quickly grab and sling them off.  Single they were no match but there were so many. Many times he would get two or three with a single slash but they kept coming. The fighting lasted for hours but seemed like days.  Losing count in his mind after twenty he guessed he must have slain thirty goblins before the few remaining ran off into the storm.  Exhausted he was able to crawl back to his rock before passing out.<br>
<br>
  The next day he woke early.  The blizzard had covered the area leaving almost no trace of the nights happening provided the occasionally stone spear sticking up or tell tell mound of a body underneath.  He quickly gathered his things and set out knowing that if he did not make it beyond the borders they would come again in greater numbers and his death would be certain.<br>
<br>
   Making good time he would spot the occasional goblin and would shoot them with his bow to keep them from running back.  He easily made the days journey and made it well beyond the borders of the ice goblins land.  The only thing left in his way was the ice and snow of the days journey that was left.<br>
<br>
   The next day went by without interference and by late that evening he saw his destination on the horizon.   He could tell from the distance that he had probably made the journey in vane and that all was well by the light he could see through the window of the cabin and the soft plume of smoke coming from the chimney.  When he got to the cabin he knocked and called out.  Answered by nothing he opened the door and was greeted by a loud growl and knocked upon his back with a large wolf standing on his chest now.  He yelled out hoping the master would hear and calm the beast.  As he did the large wolf began to lose its mass and became almost transparent and totally weightless upon him as it heeled and licked his face almost apologetically.   Getting up and out of habit trying to pet the dog only to have his hand pass right through he remember these creatures are only touched when they really want to be.  The wolf turned and trotted back inside the warm cabin and Klinget followed.  The air was thick with incense.  He looked about and the place was well kept and lit but looked like no one had really been there in a day or two.  He looked around more and opened what was a closet and as he went to open the other door the wolf quickly took its solid form it had before threatening him back from the door.  He knew the wolf would always care for its master and for some reason the creature felt they should not be disturbed at this time. <br>
<br>
   It was now getting late and he thought maybe it would be ok to stay inside as long as he didnt go passed the door and the wolf seemed to agree.  He couldnt help but wonder what was past the door as he would watch the canine phasing in the door then back out quickly making sure Klinget was not trying to get through it.  He cooked his meal and made a pallet on the floor and slept feeling safe in this place.<br>
<br>
  The next day he was awoke by the wolf taking its form just long enough to nuzzle him awake.  It was just before daybreak and he thought he may well go.  This place was safe, the goblins dared not venture near these lands for they believed they were evil(which would be good by our standards).  So packing his things back up only taking what he needed to get to the next camp he left the rest thinking they might be  more use to the owner of the cabin, seeing how bare the cupboards were.   As he stepped out he felt a cold wet nose touching his hand but when he turned the wolf had already taken its ghostly form back.  He smiled at dog and said 'good boy' as the dog  sat down shuffled its front feet excitedly and yelped happily.  He shut the door behind him and jumped as the dog poked his head through the door, how magic creatures always managed to creep him out with such tricks.  As he walked off, turning and taking the path towards the south the wolf watched him till he was out of sight.  As he walked he did so at a much more lax pace, almost as a man would through a park.  He thought about his trip and tried to figure his earnings.  He wondered where he should go for he had heard no need of his presence back in his guild hall yet.  He wondered if he would ever find out what was happening behind that door or if he would get to see the person again for that fact.............<br>
